Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Halve any large @cauliflower florets{300}(halved) and pop them onto a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden brown and tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim the @green beans{150}(trimmed and chopped into thirds).

Meanwhile, pour the cold @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}. Stir in the @basmati rice{150} and 1/4 tsp of @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam). While the rice cooks, heat a #large frying pan{} on medium heat (no oil).

Once the #frying pan{} is hot, dry-fry the @desiccated coconut{15%g}, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{1-2%minutes}, then transfer to a #bowl{} for later.

> Watch it like a hawk as it can burn easily.

Heat a drizzle of oil in the (now empty) frying pan on medium heat, then add the garlic, @ground coriander{1%tsp}, @Indonesian style spice mix{2} and @tomato puree{30%g}. Cook for ~{1%minute}.

Next, add the green beans, @coconut milk{200%ml}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water for the sauce{150%ml} to the pan. Stir to combine, bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer gently until the @British chicken breast{260%g}(diced) is cooked through ~{5-6%minutes}. Add a splash of water if it gets too thick.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, zest and halve the @lime{1/2}(zested and halved). Halve the @red chilli{1/2}(halved lengthways, deseeded and finely chopped). Add the lime zest and sliced chilli to the bowl of toasted coconut. Squeeze in a quarter of the lime juice, season with salt and mix well to combine. Set your sambal sprinkle aside.

Once the curry has thickened, season with salt and pepper. Squeeze in the remaining lime juice, stir well, then taste and add more salt, pepper and lime juice if needed. When cauliflower is roasted, add to the curry and stir through.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, then divide between your #bowls{}. Spoon the chicken and veg curry over the top and sprinkle with the coconut sambal. Enjoy!